The given polynomial is $x^3-3x^2-9x+30$, and we need to find the remainder when it's divided by $x-3$.

By the Remainder Theorem, the remainder of the division is equal to the value of the polynomial at $x=3$. So, let's evaluate the polynomial at $x=3$:

\begin{align*}
(3)^3-3(3)^2-9(3)+30 &= 27-27-27+30\\
&= 30 - 27\\
&= \boxed{3}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the remainder of the division of $x^3-3x^2-9x+30$ by $x-3$ is 3.

